05662nam a22006615i 9780773562844DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19911991xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735628447 a10.1515/97807735628442doi  a(DE-B1597)655498  a(OCoLC)732600957  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHD45bH58 1991eb 7aBUS0710002bisacsh04a382/.10421 aNiosi, Jorge, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTechnology and National Competitiveness /cJorge Niosi. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1991] 4c©1991  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables -- tFigures -- tContributors -- tIntroduction -- tTechnology, Energy, and International Trade -- tTechnological Change and International Trade -- tTechnology Intensity of US, Canadian, and Japanese Manufactures Output and Exports -- tCanadian Industrial Energy Consumption and External Trade -- tTechnological Clusters and Competitive Poles: The Case of Canadian Energy -- tState, Technology, and Competitiveness -- tTechnological Innovation and International Competitiveness -- tThe State and International Trade: Technology and Competitiveness -- tTechnological Competitiveness Considered as a Form of Structural Competitiveness -- tIndicators of Industrial Competitiveness: Results and Limitations -- tTechnological Development and Government Strategy -- tNew Modes of Competition in the Textile and Clothing Industry: Some Consequences for Third World Exporters -- tEngineering, Design Services, and Technology Transfers: The Case of the Republic of South Korea -- tIndustrial Structure and Innovation -- tOligopoly, Innovation, and Firm Competitiveness0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first part of the collection reassesses and elaborates on Nobel Prize winner Wassily Leontief's input-output model and makes use of Michael V. Posner's technology gap trade theory to examine international trade and import-export factor intensity. The contributors clearly isolate technology as a crucial factor in the foreign commerce of Canada, the US, and other industrial nations. The second part provides the theoretical background, revealing the importance of the industrialized state's ability to affect international trade by implementing technology policy. The third part analyses the role of government strategy in the development of technology in less industrialized nations faced with a fluctuating world economy and rapid technological change. The fourth part re-evaluates Shumpeterian theory, addressing the market determinants of technological change such as market structure, corporate strategy, and the size of corporations. The contributors to this volume are Bernard Bonin, François Chesnais, Lester A. Davis, Christian DeBresson, Giovanni Dosi, Faye Duchin, Philippe Faucher, K.E. Hamilton, Thomas Hatzichronoglou, Lynn Krieger Mytelka, Jorge Niosi, Jacques Perrin, and Luc Soete.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Leadership.2bisacsh1 aBonin, Bernard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChesnais, François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Lester A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDebresson, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDosi, Giovanni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuchin, Faye, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaucher, Philippe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamilton, K.E., eco